ğŸ” Iterator Types Summary

	Type					Name			Direction		Mutable?	Typical Use
	iterator				Default			Begin â†’ End		âœ… Yes		Regular forward traversal
	const_iterator			Const			Begin â†’ End		âŒ No		Read-only forward traversal
	reverse_iterator		Reverse			End â†’ Begin		âœ… Yes		Reverse traversal, modifiable
	const_reverse_iterator	Const Reverse	End â†’ Begin		âŒ No		Read-only reverse traversal

ğŸ’¡ Key Notes

	const_iterator prevents modification of the element the iterator points to, but you can still increment/decrement it like a normal iterator.

	reverse_iterator behaves like you'd expect: rbegin() gives the last element, and it traverses backwards.

	You can call .base() on a reverse iterator to get the corresponding forward iterator.

ğŸš¨ Subtle Gotcha with Reverse Iterators

	In reverse iterators, .rbegin() points to the last element, but .rend() is one before the first. So be cautious when mixing reverse and regular iterators â€” their boundaries behave oppositely.
